-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "main.installation" "Installation"
@prev "main.disclaimer"
@next "main.config"

    Installation shouldn't be to difficult.

    1) Unpack the hole archive to wherever you like.
    2) Move the files from the following directories where they belong or
       use Assign ADD to "merge" the directories to the matching system-
       directories:

	    MicroBBS/L          L:
	    MicroBBS/Libs       LIBS:
	    MicroBBS/C          C:
	    MicroBBS/Devs       DEVS:
	    MicroBBS/Locale     LOCALE:

    3) Assign BBS: to the "MicroBBS"-directory.
    4) Add the scripts "BBS:Commands/Maintenance" to your daily maintenance.
       Edit & run BBS:Commands/MakeCD0Index

    5) Configure your Mailer to start MicroBBS either direct or via the
       "StartBBS"-script:

       CLI-Args: StartBBS DEVICE,UNIT,BAUD,NODE,CONNECT,DUMMY
	     or: MicroBBS D=DEVICE,U=UNIT/N,B=BAUD/N,N=NODE/N,L=LOCAL/S,
			  C=CONNECT,O=CONFIG:

       The NODE-option requires the @{"keyfile" link "main.registration" 0}, which means that you can run
       MicroBBS only once at a time if you're not registered.

       Example for GMS: BBSCommand="Mail:Scripts/StartBBS %s %u %b %m %C"

    6) Change the BBS-@{"configuration" link "main.config"}.

@endnode
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node "main.config" "Configuration"
@prev "main.installation"
@next "main.registration"

 Setting up MicroBBS is a little bit like programming, but in a very
 simplified way. The "syntax" is very strict and easy to understand, just
 refer to the @{"example configuration" link "config.example" 0} to find out how the syntax looks like.

 There are two main types of configuration-entries. The first ones are simply
 options to define the screen, the console and similar things:

	@{"General options" link "config.options" 0}

	@{"Chatter" link "config.chatter" 0}
	@{"Configs" link "config.configs" 0}
	@{"Console" link "config.console" 0}
	@{"Screen " link "config.screen" 0}

 Only some of these options allow the special @{"%-commands" link "config.percent" 0} to be used. Refer to
 theirs documentation.

 The others are more difficult. Generaly speaking, they are all defining
 different types of commands. These commands can use other commands, either
 internal or by config defined ones. Be careful to not create loops!
 If a used command is not defined in the config, the bbs interprets it as a
 text-file and tries to type it to the output.

	@{"Internal commands" link "config.internal" 0}

	@{"Batches  " link "config.batches" 0}  - Lists of commands.
	@{"Externals" link "config.externals" 0}  - External commands.
	@{"Spawn    " link "config.spawn" 0}  - External commands with in-/output-redirection.
	@{"Menus    " link "config.menus" 0}  - Menu-definition.
	@{"Texts    " link "config.texts" 0}  - Text-files to use for output.

 All of these options allow the special @{"%-commands" link "config.percent" 0} to be used.

 All options may be defined multiple times, if an option is "single lined"
 ( e.g. @{"Log" link "config.internal" 0} or a user-defined command like: xyz.txt "Foo-Bar" ) the old
 one is simply replaced, it the option is "multi lined" ( e.g. @{"Menus" link "config.menus" 0} or
 @{"Screen" link "config.screen" 0}) the new options are added.

 It's no problem to create multiple blocks of e.g. @{"Menus" link "config.menu" 0} or @{"Texts" link "config.texts" 0}. They are
 automagically merged together.

@endnode
